WEBVTT

1
00:00:31.082 --> 00:00:33.809
<i>Last season on</i>
Star Trek: Strange New Worlds...

2
00:00:33.983 --> 00:00:35.637
<i>Do you really
still believe our futures</i>

3
00:00:35.811 --> 00:00:36.899
<i>are written in stone?</i>

4
00:00:37.073 --> 00:00:38.379
<i>All I know is that</i>

5
00:00:38.553 --> 00:00:40.685
<i>I'm not ready to let you go.</i>

6
00:00:40.859 --> 00:00:42.905
<i>Everything that happened to me</i>

7
00:00:43.166 --> 00:00:44.036
was so I could do this.

8
00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:45.342
No. this is... Marie...

9
00:00:45.516 --> 00:00:46.909
It's my destiny.

10
00:00:47.126 --> 00:00:49.215
<i>You. of all people.
can understand that.</i>

11
00:00:49.477 --> 00:00:51.653
<i>You have to tell me why things
are so weird with you and Spock.</i>

12
00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:53.829
<i>Spock and I made it very clear
with each other... no labels.</i>

13
00:00:54.003 --> 00:00:57.920
<i>no complicated expectations.
just fun times.</i>

14
00:00:58.094 --> 00:01:01.576
<i>Is this</i>
a "hit it" situation?

15
00:01:01.750 --> 00:01:03.534
It's a new future.

16
00:01:03.708 --> 00:01:06.015
It's whatever kind of adventure
we want it to be.

17
00:01:14.458 --> 00:01:18.114
<i>Captain's personal log.
Stardate 2491.5.</i>

18
00:01:18.375 --> 00:01:20.856
<i>We're at the end of
a routine mission on Tulaxar...</i>

19
00:01:21.117 --> 00:01:24.337
<i>our 15th in a row...
and if I'm being honest.</i>

20
00:01:24.512 --> 00:01:26.905
<i>this may well be
my favorite part.</i>

21
00:02:20.698 --> 00:02:22.613
Were you followed?

22
00:02:22.787 --> 00:02:24.615
- No. sir.
- And the meds?

23
00:02:24.789 --> 00:02:27.009
Handed off more than enough
to save the planet.

24
00:02:27.183 --> 00:02:28.358
Any issues being discovered?

25
00:02:28.619 --> 00:02:29.794
Nothing I couldn't handle.

26
00:02:29.968 --> 00:02:31.579
Four of the ones she drank with

27
00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:33.581
might need a day or two
to sleep it off.

28
00:02:33.755 --> 00:02:35.496
Lightweights.

29
00:02:37.193 --> 00:02:37.933
<i>Captain. we are in position.</i>

30
00:02:38.107 --> 00:02:39.412
<i>Ready to beam you up</i>

31
00:02:39.717 --> 00:02:40.805
<i>- on your order.</i>
- Copy that. Number One.

32
00:02:40.979 --> 00:02:42.807
You know what?

33
00:02:42.981 --> 00:02:44.766
We. uh...

34
00:02:46.594 --> 00:02:48.683
...we might ride a little more.

35
00:02:48.944 --> 00:02:51.120
<i>If you say so. Captain.</i>

36
00:02:51.294 --> 00:02:54.515
You know. just to be safe.

37
00:02:54.776 --> 00:02:57.126
Hyah.

38
00:03:13.751 --> 00:03:14.970
Welcome back. Captain.

39
00:03:15.231 --> 00:03:16.275
I can take
your saddle. if needed.

40
00:03:16.449 --> 00:03:17.320
Well. I. uh.

41
00:03:17.494 --> 00:03:19.104
prefer to carry my own gear.

42
00:03:19.278 --> 00:03:20.932
But thanks. Spock.

43
00:03:21.106 --> 00:03:22.543
But you knew that already.

44
00:03:22.717 --> 00:03:24.066
I felt it important to be here

45
00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:25.633
as soon as you returned
to the ship.

46
00:03:25.807 --> 00:03:28.287
You wanted to see me
in my outfit. didn't you?

47
00:03:29.201 --> 00:03:30.594
Perhaps.

48
00:03:36.208 --> 00:03:38.689
Follow me
to my quarters. Mr. Spock.

49
00:03:38.863 --> 00:03:41.344
These boots
are hard to take off alone.

50
00:03:43.215 --> 00:03:45.130
Six months. Chris. nonstop.

51
00:03:45.304 --> 00:03:47.350
That's a lot
of missions in a row.

52
00:03:47.524 --> 00:03:48.917
I'm just worried the crew

53
00:03:49.134 --> 00:03:50.614
is starting to feel
the strain. that's all.

54
00:03:50.875 --> 00:03:54.313
Look. they came to <i>Enterprise</i>
to see things. to...

55
00:03:54.487 --> 00:03:56.751
...do things.

56
00:03:57.012 --> 00:03:59.754
And the more you see
and do in the moment.

57
00:03:59.928 --> 00:04:03.540
the less you have to think
about the past. right?

58
00:04:05.281 --> 00:04:07.936
We all need weekends
once in a while.

59
00:04:08.197 --> 00:04:09.764
Even you.

60
00:04:10.547 --> 00:04:12.157
Understood. Number One.

61
00:04:12.331 --> 00:04:16.031
Not to mention. as much
as I enjoy having the conn.

62
00:04:16.205 --> 00:04:18.990
I wouldn't mind a little time
on-planet once in a while.

63
00:04:19.251 --> 00:04:20.818
Next mission. I promise.

64
00:04:20.992 --> 00:04:23.212
That might be
sooner than you think.

65
00:04:23.386 --> 00:04:26.694
Admiral April
is on his way to see you.

66
00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:30.915
I told you. Bob.

67
00:04:31.089 --> 00:04:33.265
I'm not looking for a promotion.

68
00:04:33.439 --> 00:04:34.745
Well. regardless of intent.

69
00:04:34.919 --> 00:04:36.878
you're being considered for one.

70
00:04:37.052 --> 00:04:38.880
To commodore.

71
00:04:39.054 --> 00:04:40.751
And that. as we both know.

72
00:04:40.925 --> 00:04:42.840
is a stepping stone.

73
00:04:44.668 --> 00:04:48.454
Look. I felt the same way
when I was captain.

74
00:04:48.629 --> 00:04:49.891
You just need to think about it.

75
00:04:50.065 --> 00:04:52.676
Really think.

76
00:04:53.721 --> 00:04:55.723
You just might
surprise yourself.

77
00:04:57.899 --> 00:04:59.814
How long do I have to consider?

78
00:04:59.988 --> 00:05:02.425
We'll need an answer when you
get back from the next mission.

79
00:05:02.599 --> 00:05:04.557
Where are you sending us?

80
00:05:07.517 --> 00:05:09.519
This is a fun one.

81
00:05:12.043 --> 00:05:13.262
Really?

82
00:05:16.308 --> 00:05:17.788
You haven't heard
the constant noises?

83
00:05:17.962 --> 00:05:20.182
Scotty acts like every time
I steer the ship.

84
00:05:20.356 --> 00:05:23.620
it makes his job harder.
so he added endless beeping

85
00:05:23.794 --> 00:05:26.623
to literally make my job harder.

86
00:05:28.712 --> 00:05:30.279
Are you listening?

87
00:05:31.410 --> 00:05:35.414
Sorry. I just have to get
prepared for my mentee training.

88
00:05:35.676 --> 00:05:39.331
Right. your new Academy cadet.

89
00:05:39.505 --> 00:05:40.681
When I got to <i>Enterprise.</i>

90
00:05:40.898 --> 00:05:43.031
I didn't know
anything about anything.

91
00:05:43.205 --> 00:05:44.641
and all of you helped me.

92
00:05:44.902 --> 00:05:46.556
I just want to pass
that on to the next person.

93
00:05:46.730 --> 00:05:50.691
I've been practicing my Vulcan
with Spock to improve it.

94
00:05:57.045 --> 00:05:58.873
<i>taz Nyota Uhura dwi-mâsh.</i>

95
00:05:59.047 --> 00:06:01.092
<i>tan-fi bo-shish
ner gab-no-vet âs</i>

96
00:06:01.266 --> 00:06:02.267
<i>dwoz nufezh po nen lhi-de-mosh.</i>

97
00:06:02.441 --> 00:06:04.661
Please do not speak Vulcan.

98
00:06:04.835 --> 00:06:06.924
Your accent is improper.

99
00:06:07.098 --> 00:06:11.059
I thought I got that right.

100
00:06:11.973 --> 00:06:14.062
I am fully versed
in all human dialects.

101
00:06:14.236 --> 00:06:16.891
That is all that is required
for us to communicate.

102
00:06:18.631 --> 00:06:20.808
Right. Let me start again.

103
00:06:21.069 --> 00:06:24.463
I am Ensign Uhura. but you
can call me Nyota. if you like.

104
00:06:24.637 --> 00:06:26.204
I was at the Academy
just a few years ago.

105
00:06:26.378 --> 00:06:28.119
so I know exactly
how you must feel.

106
00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:32.036
You are several years older
than I am.

107
00:06:32.210 --> 00:06:33.777
and since you are human.
it is unlikely

108
00:06:33.951 --> 00:06:35.344
you know how I feel.

109
00:06:35.692 --> 00:06:36.737
Were you present
for the <i>K'thonia</i> disaster?

110
00:06:36.911 --> 00:06:38.347
Or the <i>FFakisha</i> conflict?

111
00:06:39.304 --> 00:06:40.915
That all happened after I left.

112
00:06:41.176 --> 00:06:42.786
Your Vulcan
is poorly pronounced.

113
00:06:43.047 --> 00:06:45.484
your time at the Academy was
completely different than mine.

114
00:06:45.658 --> 00:06:48.531
It appears we do not have
many shared experiences at all.

115
00:07:00.282 --> 00:07:02.414
This is an unusual mission.

116
00:07:02.588 --> 00:07:05.026
We are to face a category ten
interstellar squall.

117
00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:06.810
something we rarely see
in the Alpha Quadrant.

118
00:07:07.071 --> 00:07:08.638
I-I've seen one once.

119
00:07:08.812 --> 00:07:11.249
a long time ago.
but not from this close.

120
00:07:11.423 --> 00:07:15.210
I think I was
in a phone box at the time.

121
00:07:15.384 --> 00:07:18.126
Such distortions
are often briefly occurring.

122
00:07:18.387 --> 00:07:20.911
This one has appeared
around the star Ithaxus.

123
00:07:21.085 --> 00:07:22.478
No explanation.

124
00:07:22.826 --> 00:07:24.088
Doesn't look like it's safe
for us to get near it.

125
00:07:24.262 --> 00:07:25.655
Any inhabited planets

126
00:07:25.829 --> 00:07:27.091
nearby
we should be worried about?

127
00:07:27.265 --> 00:07:28.136
None.

128
00:07:28.397 --> 00:07:29.528
Thank goodness.

129
00:07:29.877 --> 00:07:31.356
And that's the key element
of this mission.

130
00:07:31.530 --> 00:07:33.054
No one we have to protect.

131
00:07:33.271 --> 00:07:36.231
We are here to observe
an unusual stellar display.

132
00:07:36.405 --> 00:07:37.449
That is all.

133
00:07:37.623 --> 00:07:38.668
Oh. it sounds like

134
00:07:38.842 --> 00:07:40.365
we're going to the theater.

135
00:07:40.626 --> 00:07:42.150
Minus the Playbill.

136
00:07:42.324 --> 00:07:43.716
A theater that would likely tear

137
00:07:43.891 --> 00:07:45.022
our ship into small particles
of subspace

138
00:07:45.196 --> 00:07:46.589
should we get too close.

139
00:07:46.894 --> 00:07:48.243
Come on. Mr. Spock.
Where's your sense of adventure?

140
00:07:48.417 --> 00:07:50.114
Perhaps I did not
clearly state the part

141
00:07:50.288 --> 00:07:52.682
about being torn into
small particles of subspace.

142
00:07:53.509 --> 00:07:58.470
Interstellar storms
are like space-time gone wild.

143
00:07:58.644 --> 00:08:01.517
the very stuff of the universe.

144
00:08:01.778 --> 00:08:03.127
Don't you think a glimpse

145
00:08:03.301 --> 00:08:05.347
is worth a little risk?

146
00:08:05.521 --> 00:08:08.437
See? Now. that's the spirit.

147
00:08:25.671 --> 00:08:27.238
Keep us at arm's length. Erica.

148
00:08:27.412 --> 00:08:29.240
Aye. sir.

149
00:08:29.414 --> 00:08:30.894
Very long arms.

150
00:08:31.155 --> 00:08:32.940
I wish we could get closer. though.

151
00:08:33.114 --> 00:08:35.681
It's absolutely stunning.

152
00:08:35.856 --> 00:08:37.031
I understand the feeling.

153
00:08:37.205 --> 00:08:40.425
To actually see
something like this.

154
00:08:41.600 --> 00:08:44.168
Digital data is more relevant.

155
00:08:45.256 --> 00:08:46.779
Sensors are active.

156
00:08:47.041 --> 00:08:48.172
- Data is cogent.
- If you had to give up

157
00:08:48.433 --> 00:08:49.870
seeing this kind of thing
all the time.

158
00:08:50.044 --> 00:08:51.567
would you miss it?

159
00:08:51.828 --> 00:08:54.352
Every day.

160
00:08:55.484 --> 00:08:56.920
Yeah.

161
00:09:08.366 --> 00:09:10.499
Sir. I'm getting a comm signal.

162
00:09:10.673 --> 00:09:12.980
- Location. Nyota?
- The signal's erratic.

163
00:09:13.154 --> 00:09:16.897
but it seems to be coming
from inside the storm.

164
00:09:17.071 --> 00:09:18.376
It's a mayday. sir.

165
00:09:18.550 --> 00:09:21.118
A ship is stuck
inside the storm?

166
00:09:21.292 --> 00:09:22.859
That's what the signal's saying.

167
00:09:23.033 --> 00:09:24.382
Take us closer. Erica.

168
00:09:24.556 --> 00:09:25.906
But keep your foot
on the brakes.

169
00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:27.255
Understood. Captain.

170
00:09:32.216 --> 00:09:34.479
Not now. Scotty.

171
00:09:57.111 --> 00:09:59.069
Deeper scans suggest
signal origin

172
00:09:59.243 --> 00:10:00.723
is a buoy inside of the storm.

173
00:10:01.071 --> 00:10:02.725
- A buoy?
- It's a starship distress buoy.

174
00:10:02.899 --> 00:10:04.466
but I can't get
a lock on the signal.

175
00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:06.468
Any sign of the source
of the buoy? Any ships?

176
00:10:06.642 --> 00:10:08.644
Scanning. Captain.

177
00:10:12.604 --> 00:10:14.128
Uh-oh.

178
00:10:14.302 --> 00:10:15.956
The storm is undergoing
exponential expansion.

179
00:10:16.130 --> 00:10:17.435
You think?

180
00:10:17.783 --> 00:10:19.394
- Reverse course. Erica. fast.
- Already on it.

181
00:10:53.254 --> 00:10:54.733
We have life support.

182
00:10:54.995 --> 00:10:57.345
Unfortunately. that is
the extent of the good news.

183
00:10:57.519 --> 00:11:00.130
No weapons functionality. Zero.

184
00:11:00.304 --> 00:11:01.523
Long-range comms are down.

185
00:11:01.784 --> 00:11:02.915
Transporters are offline.

186
00:11:03.090 --> 00:11:05.222
Not sure when they'll
be fixed. or if.

187
00:11:05.396 --> 00:11:07.529
We have only the barest amount

188
00:11:07.790 --> 00:11:09.922
of impulse power. For now.

189
00:11:10.184 --> 00:11:12.273
- Warp?
- Out of the question.

190
00:11:12.447 --> 00:11:13.839
Look. our problem is.

191
00:11:14.014 --> 00:11:15.493
we lost all our iridium.

192
00:11:15.667 --> 00:11:17.582
Without it. we can't ignite
the warp engines.

193
00:11:17.756 --> 00:11:19.454
We're basically stuck here.

194
00:11:19.628 --> 00:11:21.064
And do we know where "here" is?

195
00:11:21.325 --> 00:11:22.587
All we've been able
to determine is.

196
00:11:22.761 --> 00:11:24.024
the stellar storm somehow pulled

197
00:11:24.198 --> 00:11:25.634
the ship into a warp field.

198
00:11:25.895 --> 00:11:27.679
The stars aren't lining up
to give us a location.

199
00:11:27.897 --> 00:11:29.638
but we think it's just the main
computer coming back on line.

200
00:11:29.812 --> 00:11:31.335
Okay.

201
00:11:32.554 --> 00:11:34.817
Deploy a locator and send
out a mayday. Let's use a flare.

202
00:11:34.991 --> 00:11:36.688
- On it.
- Short-range scans

203
00:11:36.862 --> 00:11:38.734
suggest we can only
extrapolate our position.

204
00:11:38.908 --> 00:11:40.518
Of the four planets
scanned so far.

205
00:11:40.692 --> 00:11:41.650
three are M-class.

206
00:11:41.824 --> 00:11:43.130
Inhabited? Anyone who

207
00:11:43.304 --> 00:11:44.957
- might give us a hand?
- Impossible to tell.

208
00:11:45.132 --> 00:11:46.785
given our current
sensor capabilities.

209
00:11:47.047 --> 00:11:49.614
But we have detected iridium
on the nearest M-class planet...

210
00:11:49.788 --> 00:11:51.703
a few hours' journey with
our current impulse engines.

211
00:11:51.877 --> 00:11:53.531
And one of our shuttles
is still functional enough

212
00:11:53.705 --> 00:11:55.707
to get us to the surface.
I think.

213
00:11:57.666 --> 00:11:58.928
Well. Number One.

214
00:11:59.102 --> 00:12:02.018
you wanted a mission
on a strange new world.

215
00:12:02.192 --> 00:12:03.933
Looks like you got one.

216
00:12:05.152 --> 00:12:06.762
<i>Curie. <i>this is Enterprise.</i>

217
00:12:06.936 --> 00:12:08.807
<i>You are now entering
the planet's upper atmosphere.</i>

218
00:12:08.981 --> 00:12:11.071
Heading towards
the last known iridium location.

219
00:12:11.245 --> 00:12:13.377
The land mass
is quite choppy down there.

220
00:12:13.551 --> 00:12:15.075
We're five-by-five.
We might have to land

221
00:12:15.249 --> 00:12:16.467
pretty far from the signal.

222
00:12:16.641 --> 00:12:18.600
There aren't any closer options.

223
00:13:22.794 --> 00:13:24.709
The iridium's over there.

224
00:13:33.544 --> 00:13:36.765
Near what is definitely a volcano.

225
00:13:49.647 --> 00:13:51.519
Um...

226
00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:54.609
I'm detecting life signs.

227
00:13:56.263 --> 00:13:57.742
What kind of life signs?

228
00:13:57.916 --> 00:13:59.527
Large.

229
00:14:00.441 --> 00:14:02.269
Taller than us?

230
00:14:02.443 --> 00:14:03.618
Much taller.

231
00:14:07.926 --> 00:14:12.279
Is there a way around that?

232
00:14:13.497 --> 00:14:14.672
No.

233
00:14:14.846 --> 00:14:16.848
We want the iridium.

234
00:14:17.022 --> 00:14:20.548
we have to get past that.

235
00:14:28.164 --> 00:14:29.557
Great news.

236
00:14:34.126 --> 00:14:35.519
I've got a fix on the creature.

237
00:14:35.693 --> 00:14:37.260
That's not the problem.
It's. uh...

238
00:14:37.434 --> 00:14:39.523
<i>trying to do something about it.</i>

239
00:14:39.697 --> 00:14:41.569
- Can't you just stun it?
<i>- Well. if I had</i>

240
00:14:41.743 --> 00:14:44.224
<i>phasers. sure. Um...</i>

241
00:14:44.398 --> 00:14:45.834
I might be able to send a bolt

242
00:14:46.095 --> 00:14:47.618
of electricity. but
I don't want to kill the laddie.

243
00:14:47.792 --> 00:14:50.578
We should probably determine
what it can withstand first.

244
00:14:51.796 --> 00:14:53.494
What are you doing?

245
00:15:03.417 --> 00:15:04.722
Why did you just shoot it?

246
00:15:04.896 --> 00:15:06.637
Wha... I was on stun.

247
00:15:06.898 --> 00:15:08.378
And you saw. Nothing happened.

248
00:15:08.596 --> 00:15:09.553
The laddie may be a wee bit

249
00:15:09.727 --> 00:15:11.033
stronger than we anticipated.

250
00:15:11.338 --> 00:15:12.948
"Laddie"? You think
that's what I talk like?

251
00:15:13.122 --> 00:15:14.515
- That's totally what you talk like.
<i>- Fine.</i>

252
00:15:18.606 --> 00:15:20.260
Something's just
grabbed the ship.

253
00:15:40.932 --> 00:15:42.847
<i>Space.</i>

254
00:15:43.979 --> 00:15:45.981
<i>The final frontier.</i>

255
00:15:47.896 --> 00:15:51.639
<i>These are the voyages
of the starship</i> Enterprise.

256
00:15:52.814 --> 00:15:55.512
<i>Its five-year mission:</i>

257
00:15:55.686 --> 00:15:58.689
<i>to explore strange new worlds...</i>

258
00:15:59.908 --> 00:16:03.215
<i>...to seek out new life</i>

259
00:16:03.390 --> 00:16:05.957
<i>and new civilizations...</i>

260
00:16:06.958 --> 00:16:10.962
<i>...to boldly go
where no one has gone before.</i>

261
00:17:38.528 --> 00:17:40.095
Where did they come from?

262
00:17:40.487 --> 00:17:42.053
Unclear. Captain.
Our sensors are functioning

263
00:17:42.227 --> 00:17:43.577
below normal parameters.

264
00:17:43.968 --> 00:17:44.795
They seem to have
attached some kind

265
00:17:44.969 --> 00:17:46.710
of energy tendrils.

266
00:17:46.971 --> 00:17:48.277
They are similar to our
tractor beams. but the style

267
00:17:48.451 --> 00:17:49.583
is one I am not familiar with.

268
00:17:49.757 --> 00:17:50.845
Do we have any weapons? Shields?

269
00:17:51.106 --> 00:17:52.324
No. the shields are still

270
00:17:52.716 --> 00:17:54.501
not functioning. Captain.
and Scotty cannot

271
00:17:54.675 --> 00:17:56.894
repair the weapons
without iridium.

272
00:17:57.068 --> 00:17:58.287
We-we are crippled.

273
00:17:58.461 --> 00:17:59.375
They're literally
towing us away.

274
00:17:59.549 --> 00:18:00.637
Do we have impulse? Anything?

275
00:18:00.898 --> 00:18:02.378
No. using impulse engines

276
00:18:02.639 --> 00:18:04.598
would be like trying
to free ourselves from a boat

277
00:18:04.772 --> 00:18:06.687
using a pair of flippers.

278
00:18:06.861 --> 00:18:08.079
Small flippers.

279
00:18:08.384 --> 00:18:09.907
Flippers that could be
lost at any time.

280
00:18:10.081 --> 00:18:11.648
Comms are
still functioning. sir.

281
00:18:11.909 --> 00:18:13.171
As is our universal translator.

282
00:18:13.433 --> 00:18:14.738
Does anyone recognize that ship?

283
00:18:14.912 --> 00:18:16.044
I do not.

284
00:18:16.305 --> 00:18:17.132
and it does not exist
in our database.

285
00:18:17.306 --> 00:18:19.003
Hail them. Nyota.

286
00:18:19.351 --> 00:18:20.831
Let's try the friendly approach
first. We don't have much else

287
00:18:21.005 --> 00:18:22.442
- to work with.
- Hailing them. sir.

288
00:18:22.616 --> 00:18:24.008
This is Captain Christopher Pike

289
00:18:24.269 --> 00:18:25.488
of the starship <i>Enterprise.</i>

290
00:18:25.662 --> 00:18:27.185
You seem to have...

291
00:18:28.360 --> 00:18:32.495
...you seem to have accidentally
taken hold of our ship.

292
00:18:33.627 --> 00:18:34.541
Anything?

293
00:18:34.715 --> 00:18:37.369
They're responding. sir.

294
00:18:39.981 --> 00:18:41.591
<i>I am Battle Commander Cassell.</i>

295
00:18:41.765 --> 00:18:43.724
<i>We didn't attach
our tethers by accident.</i>

296
00:18:43.898 --> 00:18:45.987
<i>We seized
your damaged ship as salvage.</i>

297
00:18:46.161 --> 00:18:50.470
<i>Your ship and its resources
are now our property.</i>

298
00:18:51.514 --> 00:18:52.994
Still nothing from the ship.

299
00:18:53.168 --> 00:18:54.996
Scotty said
he'd come right back.

300
00:18:55.170 --> 00:18:57.259
He didn't. Typical.

301
00:18:57.433 --> 00:18:58.608
I don't like it.

302
00:18:58.869 --> 00:19:00.741
We may be on our own.
at least for now.

303
00:19:01.393 --> 00:19:03.439
We need to get a better idea
of what we're facing.

304
00:19:03.613 --> 00:19:04.962
What about the new...

305
00:19:05.136 --> 00:19:06.355
vaporization thingy?

306
00:19:06.529 --> 00:19:08.270
You know what it's called.

307
00:19:08.444 --> 00:19:10.098
Scotty's not even here
to get annoyed.

308
00:19:10.272 --> 00:19:11.229
Just makes me feel better.

309
00:19:11.403 --> 00:19:12.753
The phasers have been modified

310
00:19:12.927 --> 00:19:15.495
with a contained
disintegration function.

311
00:19:15.669 --> 00:19:18.585
We need to get a clear shot
at that copse of trees.

312
00:19:18.759 --> 00:19:21.805
Maybe we can see the "laddie"
that's hiding behind it.

313
00:19:21.979 --> 00:19:23.067
<i>Commander Cassell.</i>

314
00:19:23.241 --> 00:19:25.592
we are members of Starfleet.

315
00:19:27.028 --> 00:19:29.770
Any actions against us
will be seen

316
00:19:29.944 --> 00:19:32.120
as actions against the
United Federation of Planets.

317
00:19:32.294 --> 00:19:34.078
<i>We aren't familiar
with your Starfleet</i>

318
00:19:34.339 --> 00:19:37.473
<i>or Federation. but if you're
in league with the Dol'drm.</i>

319
00:19:37.647 --> 00:19:39.519
<i>we will destroy you.</i>

320
00:19:44.349 --> 00:19:45.437
What?

321
00:19:45.742 --> 00:19:47.048
Be careful
what you say. Captain.

322
00:19:47.222 --> 00:19:48.832
If they are not familiar
with Starfleet.

323
00:19:49.006 --> 00:19:50.660
it is possible
that they are pre-warp.

324
00:19:50.834 --> 00:19:52.619
They may be seizing our ship
to learn about our technology.

325
00:19:52.793 --> 00:19:54.925
which is strictly
against our prime directive.

326
00:19:55.099 --> 00:19:56.536
They have the ship. Spock.

327
00:19:56.710 --> 00:19:58.102
Right now talking
is our only way out.

328
00:19:58.276 --> 00:19:59.756
Allow me to scan it further.

329
00:20:00.017 --> 00:20:01.976
Perhaps you could stall.

330
00:20:03.630 --> 00:20:06.981
We are not familiar
with the Dol'drm.

331
00:20:07.155 --> 00:20:08.678
We're new
to this region of space.

332
00:20:08.852 --> 00:20:10.637
and if you don't know
the Federation.

333
00:20:10.811 --> 00:20:12.203
we also don't know you.

334
00:20:12.377 --> 00:20:13.683
<i>We are at war. Captain.</i>

335
00:20:14.031 --> 00:20:16.381
<i>with a terrible
and destructive enemy.</i>

336
00:20:16.556 --> 00:20:18.470
<i>and as part
of our wartime covenants.</i>

337
00:20:18.645 --> 00:20:21.561
<i>we have seized your ship
as scrap for our war effort.</i>

338
00:20:21.735 --> 00:20:23.954
<i>If you are not aligned
with the Dol'drm.</i>

339
00:20:24.128 --> 00:20:26.174
<i>you will be released
when we return home.</i>

340
00:20:26.348 --> 00:20:28.263
You can't just take our ship
without consequences.

341
00:20:28.524 --> 00:20:31.614
<i>And yet you have shown us none.
This discussion is over.</i>

342
00:20:31.788 --> 00:20:33.616
Commander. we do have weapons.

343
00:20:33.877 --> 00:20:36.184
and Starfleet has more...
a lot more.

344
00:20:36.358 --> 00:20:37.794
Do you really want us
to turn all of them on you

345
00:20:38.055 --> 00:20:39.666
just to prove our point?

346
00:20:43.800 --> 00:20:45.323
Why don't you come aboard?

347
00:20:48.022 --> 00:20:50.154
I can show you myself.
and we can discuss ways

348
00:20:50.328 --> 00:20:52.461
that the Federation
can help you.

349
00:20:55.246 --> 00:20:57.031
<i>I don't think
this will be useful.</i>

350
00:20:57.901 --> 00:21:00.817
<i>But if you have weapons
to show us. personally.</i>

351
00:21:00.991 --> 00:21:02.340
<i>I'll come on board to see them.</i>

352
00:21:02.558 --> 00:21:04.255
That-That's not exactly
what I said. I...

353
00:21:04.429 --> 00:21:05.648
<i>End communication.</i>

354
00:21:07.041 --> 00:21:09.217
Okay. not ideal.

355
00:21:15.919 --> 00:21:17.660
You sure this is going to work?

356
00:21:17.921 --> 00:21:20.576
Not in the slightest.

357
00:21:22.491 --> 00:21:24.362
Well. at least we're talking.

358
00:21:24.536 --> 00:21:26.669
I am afraid our circumstance is...

359
00:21:27.975 --> 00:21:30.064
...slightly more complicated
than we realized. Captain.

360
00:21:30.238 --> 00:21:32.196
I have determined
our current location.

361
00:21:33.328 --> 00:21:36.374
Scans have revealed that
we are in the Sol system.

362
00:21:36.548 --> 00:21:37.854
Sol?

363
00:21:38.028 --> 00:21:39.900
Spock. this
doesn't make any sense.

364
00:21:40.074 --> 00:21:41.771
Three M-class worlds?

365
00:21:41.989 --> 00:21:44.426
The stellar storm created
an incredible amount of energy.

366
00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:46.558
far beyond
what our ship is capable of.

367
00:21:46.733 --> 00:21:50.693
However. where it sent us
is less relevant than when.

368
00:21:52.477 --> 00:21:56.220
Currently. we are
65 million years in the past.

369
00:22:00.137 --> 00:22:03.880
The planet Commander Cassell
is dragging us toward is Mars.

370
00:22:04.054 --> 00:22:05.752
Mars?

371
00:22:06.840 --> 00:22:10.452
Then that would mean the planet
that Una flew the shuttle to...

372
00:22:13.716 --> 00:22:15.762
Is Earth. Captain.

373
00:22:35.956 --> 00:22:37.653
So. according to <i>Enterprise.</i>
we can't harm

374
00:22:37.827 --> 00:22:40.264
any native life because doing so
could wreck the future.

375
00:22:40.438 --> 00:22:42.397
Unfortunately.
the dinosaurs do not share

376
00:22:42.571 --> 00:22:46.618
our temporal prohibitions
when it comes to eating us.

377
00:22:48.490 --> 00:22:50.100
I have an idea.

378
00:22:50.274 --> 00:22:51.841
But I don't think either of you
are gonna like it.

379
00:22:52.015 --> 00:22:53.234
Oh. we are way

380
00:22:53.408 --> 00:22:55.540
- past that.
- Yeah.

381
00:22:55.715 --> 00:22:56.890
What you got. boss?

382
00:22:58.543 --> 00:22:59.762
<i>They have never heard</i>

383
00:22:59.936 --> 00:23:01.546
of Starfleet or the Federation

384
00:23:01.721 --> 00:23:03.157
because neither will exist

385
00:23:03.418 --> 00:23:04.811
for millions of years.

386
00:23:05.072 --> 00:23:06.377
It may be challenging

387
00:23:06.595 --> 00:23:08.640
to form a shared frame
of reference. Captain.

388
00:23:08.815 --> 00:23:10.947
It shouldn't be that different
from any first contact

389
00:23:11.121 --> 00:23:12.557
with a pre-warp species.

390
00:23:12.775 --> 00:23:15.125
Except you invited her
on board your starship.

391
00:23:15.996 --> 00:23:17.432
Yeah. there is that.

392
00:23:17.693 --> 00:23:19.826
Look. by the time
our present comes around.

393
00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:21.784
Mars has been lifeless for eons.

394
00:23:21.958 --> 00:23:23.655
I'm going to wager
that nothing we say here

395
00:23:23.917 --> 00:23:25.396
is going to change the future.

396
00:23:25.614 --> 00:23:28.051
so long as she doesn't leave
the ship with anything material.

397
00:23:28.225 --> 00:23:30.750
Alternatively.
any single one of our actions

398
00:23:30.924 --> 00:23:33.056
could result in
our future never occurring.

399
00:23:33.317 --> 00:23:35.232
Okay. so out of
an abundance of caution.

400
00:23:35.493 --> 00:23:36.756
we'll keep her from...

401
00:23:36.930 --> 00:23:38.061
Everything?

402
00:23:38.322 --> 00:23:39.759
It feels like
you're not helping.

403
00:23:39.933 --> 00:23:42.283
That's odd.

404
00:23:43.501 --> 00:23:46.374
Scanners seem to have detected
something on the hull.

405
00:23:46.548 --> 00:23:48.724
<i>Possible hull breach on Deck Seven.</i>

406
00:23:48.898 --> 00:23:50.160
We're on Deck Seven.

407
00:23:50.334 --> 00:23:52.423
No adjustment
in air temperature. Strange.

408
00:23:52.597 --> 00:23:53.381
Where?

409
00:23:53.555 --> 00:23:55.078
Corridor.

410
00:24:03.347 --> 00:24:05.219
Commander Cassell.

411
00:24:14.402 --> 00:24:16.012
I'm Captain Pike.

412
00:24:16.186 --> 00:24:18.101
You are... short.

413
00:24:18.275 --> 00:24:21.322
Our-our planet's
a little heavier than yours.

414
00:24:21.496 --> 00:24:24.325
Hence this unpleasant
artificial gravity on your ship?

415
00:24:24.499 --> 00:24:26.501
- Too unpleasant? We can adjust.
- No need.

416
00:24:26.675 --> 00:24:28.677
We're obviously considerably
stronger than you are.

417
00:24:28.851 --> 00:24:30.200
How did you get inside our ship?

418
00:24:30.374 --> 00:24:31.941
We phased through your wall.

419
00:24:33.813 --> 00:24:35.815
Do you not have
phasing technology?

420
00:24:35.989 --> 00:24:39.166
Well. no. but we have
transporters which allow us...

421
00:24:39.427 --> 00:24:41.777
Which we can gladly discuss
at a later juncture.

422
00:24:41.951 --> 00:24:44.736
Allow me to introduce
our science officer Spock.

423
00:24:44.911 --> 00:24:48.915
Dr. M'Benga.
and our engineer Mr. Scott.

424
00:24:51.004 --> 00:24:52.266
Forgive me if I don't.

425
00:24:52.527 --> 00:24:53.745
My guards
are under standing orders

426
00:24:53.920 --> 00:24:55.573
to kill anyone
who comes too close.

427
00:24:55.835 --> 00:24:57.227
Okay.

428
00:24:58.446 --> 00:25:00.840
I assure you.
that won't be necessary. Commander.

429
00:25:01.014 --> 00:25:03.277
- You're here as our guests.
- We're here as your captors

430
00:25:03.451 --> 00:25:05.888
to see your weaponry.
Captain Pike.

431
00:25:06.062 --> 00:25:07.368
Commander. you are not
our enemy.

432
00:25:07.542 --> 00:25:09.805
That assessment is mine to make.

433
00:25:10.066 --> 00:25:12.721
You would do the same
in my position. would you not?

434
00:25:16.333 --> 00:25:18.292
Our transporter typically
sweeps our visitors

435
00:25:18.466 --> 00:25:19.641
for health and safety.

436
00:25:19.902 --> 00:25:21.948
Would you permit me
to examine you?

437
00:25:22.122 --> 00:25:25.081
To ensure you haven't brought
any pathogens aboard

438
00:25:25.255 --> 00:25:28.650
and that you can handle any
you might find aboard as well.

439
00:25:28.824 --> 00:25:31.261
Well. I am confident
our biological prophylaxis

440
00:25:31.435 --> 00:25:34.090
will keep all parties safe.

441
00:25:34.264 --> 00:25:36.092
However. given I also
trained in medicine.

442
00:25:36.266 --> 00:25:38.703
I am curious
to see what technology you have.

443
00:25:39.835 --> 00:25:42.882
After that. we will see
your weapons systems.

444
00:25:50.890 --> 00:25:52.413
Stun?

445
00:25:52.587 --> 00:25:56.852
Your plan is to get close
and just use stun?

446
00:25:57.113 --> 00:25:58.767
- That is correct.
- I'll remind you.

447
00:25:58.941 --> 00:26:00.769
we tried it.
It didn't faze it one bit.

448
00:26:00.943 --> 00:26:02.205
I mean. we could just
disintegrate it.

449
00:26:02.379 --> 00:26:03.728
if it wasn't for. you know.

450
00:26:03.946 --> 00:26:05.687
the whole "destroy
the entire future" part.

451
00:26:05.861 --> 00:26:08.081
I'm going to get close enough
so it opens its mouth.

452
00:26:08.255 --> 00:26:11.084
shoot in its soft palate.
and hope it works.

453
00:26:11.345 --> 00:26:13.434
And that it doesn't decide
you're maybe a delicious snack

454
00:26:13.608 --> 00:26:14.914
with several more
yummies nearby?

455
00:26:15.088 --> 00:26:16.263
We'll kill it
if it gets to that.

456
00:26:16.437 --> 00:26:17.742
Don't.

457
00:26:18.004 --> 00:26:19.309
We genuinely don't know
the future effects

458
00:26:19.483 --> 00:26:20.789
of anything we might do here.

459
00:26:23.357 --> 00:26:26.273
I'll stun. and then we run.

460
00:26:26.447 --> 00:26:27.274
Crazy.

461
00:26:27.448 --> 00:26:28.797
Dangerous.

462
00:26:29.058 --> 00:26:31.278
Maybe even insane.
But I'm kind of impressed.

463
00:26:31.452 --> 00:26:32.757
Is that weird?

464
00:26:46.467 --> 00:26:48.208
Hey! Dinosaur!

465
00:26:48.382 --> 00:26:50.688
You there!

466
00:27:28.596 --> 00:27:30.859
Did it eat her?

467
00:27:31.033 --> 00:27:32.208
It's not chewing.

468
00:27:34.167 --> 00:27:36.647
It's asleep. Stun worked!

469
00:27:39.955 --> 00:27:41.783
And you didn't kill him.

470
00:27:42.044 --> 00:27:43.350
Nice work.

471
00:27:43.524 --> 00:27:47.484
Let's move. Before <i>she</i> wakes up.

472
00:27:47.658 --> 00:27:49.573
- She?
- Yeah.

473
00:27:49.747 --> 00:27:52.141
It's not a "laddie."
it's a "lassie."

474
00:27:56.711 --> 00:27:59.148
There are many different types
of people on this ship.

475
00:27:59.322 --> 00:28:00.367
In this room alone. we have

476
00:28:00.541 --> 00:28:03.065
humans. Vulcans and Tellarites.

477
00:28:03.239 --> 00:28:04.371
As members of Starfleet.
we've encountered

478
00:28:04.545 --> 00:28:05.546
countless other species.

479
00:28:05.807 --> 00:28:07.330
We come from different planets.

480
00:28:07.504 --> 00:28:09.071
but we have ways
to work together.

481
00:28:09.289 --> 00:28:12.640
And none of these countless
species wish to destroy you?

482
00:28:12.814 --> 00:28:15.773
- Members of the Federation. no.
- Ah.

483
00:28:15.947 --> 00:28:18.167
but I get the feeling others do?

484
00:28:18.341 --> 00:28:19.951
Well. those that don't like us

485
00:28:20.213 --> 00:28:21.736
aren't against just one of us.
they're against all of us.

486
00:28:21.910 --> 00:28:23.738
Our unity is our best deterrent.

487
00:28:23.912 --> 00:28:25.957
Again. because of your weapons?

488
00:28:27.089 --> 00:28:29.265
Federation members do bring
weapons to the table.

489
00:28:29.439 --> 00:28:32.312
but that same unity means we
often do not have to use them.

490
00:28:32.573 --> 00:28:34.749
I must admit.
I have difficulty imagining

491
00:28:34.923 --> 00:28:37.012
such an alliance as this.

492
00:28:37.186 --> 00:28:39.058
Many worlds working together.

493
00:28:39.319 --> 00:28:40.320
Technically. we...

494
00:28:40.494 --> 00:28:42.191
we don't just
work together. we...

495
00:28:42.365 --> 00:28:43.714
we pick up a lot of stuff
from each other.

496
00:28:43.888 --> 00:28:45.629
None of those others

497
00:28:45.803 --> 00:28:48.719
are concerned that you'll turn
their weapons against them?

498
00:28:48.893 --> 00:28:51.113
Sometimes it's just recipes.

499
00:28:51.287 --> 00:28:53.246
Or...

500
00:28:53.420 --> 00:28:55.030
music. Whatever we share.

501
00:28:55.204 --> 00:28:57.163
it tends to add up

502
00:28:57.424 --> 00:28:58.990
to more than
the sum of its parts.

503
00:28:59.165 --> 00:29:01.080
I only know my world

504
00:29:01.254 --> 00:29:02.429
and the Dol'drm.

505
00:29:02.603 --> 00:29:04.257
"Alien" to me means evil.

506
00:29:04.431 --> 00:29:05.562
Humans

507
00:29:05.823 --> 00:29:07.129
have a way of saying.
when it comes

508
00:29:07.347 --> 00:29:09.218
to facing an enemy.
the carrot or the stick.

509
00:29:09.392 --> 00:29:11.394
What is a carrot?

510
00:29:11.568 --> 00:29:13.744
Is it a weapon of some sort?

511
00:29:13.918 --> 00:29:16.138
I imagine it is more persuasive
than a stick.

512
00:29:16.312 --> 00:29:17.966
Yeah. it is.

513
00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:19.489
but not in the way
that you're thinking.

514
00:29:19.663 --> 00:29:20.969
No. um. you eat a carrot.

515
00:29:21.143 --> 00:29:22.492
It's a reward.

516
00:29:22.666 --> 00:29:24.538
Uh. it helps
to form an alliance.

517
00:29:24.712 --> 00:29:26.931
No. the stick
is the only weapon.

518
00:29:28.107 --> 00:29:30.283
So you're benevolent
until that no longer works.

519
00:29:30.457 --> 00:29:32.285
and only then are you hostile?

520
00:29:32.459 --> 00:29:34.983
It's a strategy of sorts.

521
00:29:35.157 --> 00:29:36.289
I'm happy to say

522
00:29:36.550 --> 00:29:38.334
we have no issues
of contamination.

523
00:29:38.508 --> 00:29:40.119
You clearly dedicate
many resources

524
00:29:40.293 --> 00:29:41.424
to this medical facility.

525
00:29:41.598 --> 00:29:43.818
Frankly. it's
something of a wonder

526
00:29:43.992 --> 00:29:46.342
to see so few occupied beds
or injuries.

527
00:29:46.516 --> 00:29:48.083
Captain Pike.

528
00:29:48.431 --> 00:29:51.913
perhaps I have been too quick
to judge you and your crew.

529
00:29:52.087 --> 00:29:54.045
It appears
you are not the enemies

530
00:29:54.307 --> 00:29:56.004
we perceived you to be.

531
00:29:56.178 --> 00:29:57.527
Glad to hear it.

532
00:29:58.354 --> 00:30:00.574
But appearances
can be deceiving.

533
00:30:00.748 --> 00:30:02.532
Do you have this saying. too?

534
00:30:02.706 --> 00:30:04.882
Take me to your weapons systems.

535
00:30:05.056 --> 00:30:08.408
and then I may better
understand what this alliance

536
00:30:08.582 --> 00:30:10.279
with its many points of view

537
00:30:10.453 --> 00:30:12.499
and carrots and sticks
has to offer.

538
00:30:14.936 --> 00:30:16.894
Of course.

539
00:30:17.460 --> 00:30:18.983
<i>Phasers and photon torpedoes
are your ship's primary weapons?</i>

540
00:30:19.158 --> 00:30:21.029
But not the part most used.

541
00:30:21.203 --> 00:30:24.250
I assume you are referring
to defensive systems?

542
00:30:24.424 --> 00:30:26.687
You mentioned
the use of shields.

543
00:30:26.861 --> 00:30:28.341
Our shields are damaged.

544
00:30:28.515 --> 00:30:30.560
Given time.
our engineering station

545
00:30:30.734 --> 00:30:33.650
or our science station will find
ways of repairing our systems.

546
00:30:33.824 --> 00:30:36.914
What is the main purpose
of your science station?

547
00:30:37.088 --> 00:30:38.829
Is it to assess
the vulnerability

548
00:30:39.003 --> 00:30:40.266
of potential enemies?

549
00:30:43.486 --> 00:30:45.140
Science allows us
a broad understanding

550
00:30:45.401 --> 00:30:47.534
of every culture we encounter
so we can share strengths

551
00:30:47.708 --> 00:30:49.579
and compensate for each other's
respective weaknesses.

552
00:30:49.753 --> 00:30:51.407
Understanding other cultures
has allowed us

553
00:30:51.581 --> 00:30:53.844
to advance faster
than if we were alone.

554
00:30:55.194 --> 00:30:57.152
I am sorry for your loss?

555
00:30:57.979 --> 00:30:59.981
You used the word "alone."

556
00:31:00.155 --> 00:31:01.374
Our people

557
00:31:01.765 --> 00:31:04.812
have ten individual words
for such a state.

558
00:31:04.986 --> 00:31:07.075
differentiated
by emotional inflection.

559
00:31:07.249 --> 00:31:08.859
I'm sorry. I don't follow.

560
00:31:09.033 --> 00:31:12.123
Your translating machine
used the word "widower."

561
00:31:13.690 --> 00:31:15.866
And so my condolences.

562
00:31:20.741 --> 00:31:24.614
Our captains are not permitted
relationships during war.

563
00:31:24.788 --> 00:31:30.316
They leave us vulnerable.
too hesitant to sacrifice.

564
00:31:30.490 --> 00:31:32.709
And we have always been at war.

565
00:31:33.623 --> 00:31:35.973
Well. isn't love
part of what we fight for?

566
00:31:39.020 --> 00:31:41.240
If not that. then...

567
00:31:42.458 --> 00:31:45.026
Have you ever seen
my homeworld of Mars?

568
00:31:47.768 --> 00:31:50.074
We are not familiar with
the current condition of Mars.

569
00:31:50.249 --> 00:31:51.902
If the ship's scanners
are repaired.

570
00:31:52.076 --> 00:31:54.035
will you pull it up on-screen?

571
00:31:55.123 --> 00:31:56.385
Please.

572
00:32:03.610 --> 00:32:05.525
- It's beautiful.
- Yes.

573
00:32:05.699 --> 00:32:08.832
But there is something
more important for you to see.

574
00:32:09.006 --> 00:32:12.096
Turn the planet view
173 degrees.

575
00:32:18.189 --> 00:32:19.843
Valles Marineris.

576
00:32:20.061 --> 00:32:23.586
That crater was caused
when the Dol'drm crashed a ship

577
00:32:23.760 --> 00:32:27.677
onto the surface
and fed on our world.

578
00:32:29.288 --> 00:32:30.463
The only way to stop them was

579
00:32:30.637 --> 00:32:33.596
to tear away
the very land around them.

580
00:32:33.770 --> 00:32:35.511
The invaders died.

581
00:32:35.729 --> 00:32:40.951
But that crater and two million
lives is the price we paid.

582
00:32:41.604 --> 00:32:43.824
- That's horrible.
- That's why your discussions

583
00:32:43.998 --> 00:32:45.521
of cultures. of science.

584
00:32:45.695 --> 00:32:48.089
although kind and hopeful.

585
00:32:48.263 --> 00:32:49.569
are not relevant.

586
00:32:49.786 --> 00:32:52.528
What we need to do
is destroy the Dol'drm

587
00:32:52.702 --> 00:32:54.661
before they devour
the rest of our planet

588
00:32:54.835 --> 00:32:56.576
and turn it all
into a red wasteland.

589
00:32:56.750 --> 00:32:58.621
Well. have you ever tried
communicating with the Dol'drm?

590
00:32:58.795 --> 00:33:00.623
We cannot.
They are insects.

591
00:33:00.884 --> 00:33:03.844
They do not speak
or reason as we do.

592
00:33:04.018 --> 00:33:07.543
They simply feed
and move forward.

593
00:33:07.717 --> 00:33:09.197
You may have other options.

594
00:33:09.371 --> 00:33:12.896
Some on our planet argued this.

595
00:33:13.070 --> 00:33:15.682
They believed there were
other ways to deal with them.

596
00:33:15.856 --> 00:33:18.249
As they talked. we died.

597
00:33:18.424 --> 00:33:20.991
There's only one thing
that's ever worked.

598
00:33:21.165 --> 00:33:22.645
Force.

599
00:33:23.472 --> 00:33:25.300
What if we
could offer you something

600
00:33:25.474 --> 00:33:26.823
that would work without weapons?

601
00:33:28.216 --> 00:33:31.175
Something only Starfleet's
resources can provide?

602
00:33:33.352 --> 00:33:35.919
The Federation have met maybe

603
00:33:36.093 --> 00:33:38.574
65 different insectoid species.

604
00:33:38.748 --> 00:33:41.577
Of those. 17 of them don't
use sonic communication.

605
00:33:41.751 --> 00:33:42.970
like us.

606
00:33:43.144 --> 00:33:44.885
This is where
xenoanthropology helps.

607
00:33:45.059 --> 00:33:46.408
We've been able to design
multiple systems

608
00:33:46.669 --> 00:33:48.367
that work for creatures
who communicate

609
00:33:48.541 --> 00:33:50.630
using light. touch or.

610
00:33:50.804 --> 00:33:53.197
in one particularly
difficult case. smell.

611
00:33:53.372 --> 00:33:57.463
Which stunk.

612
00:33:57.637 --> 00:34:01.249
But it did allow us.
eventually. to speak with them.

613
00:34:02.337 --> 00:34:03.860
Fascinating.

614
00:34:04.034 --> 00:34:05.471
You keep insisting it's impossible

615
00:34:05.645 --> 00:34:07.734
to communicate with the Dol'drm.

616
00:34:07.995 --> 00:34:09.649
If we find out we can.
maybe we could find a way

617
00:34:09.823 --> 00:34:10.867
to stop them without weapons.

618
00:34:11.128 --> 00:34:12.826
What if we could end your war?

619
00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:16.177
What if we could
offer them something?

620
00:34:16.351 --> 00:34:18.745
Isn't it worth
a brief consideration?

621
00:34:21.182 --> 00:34:22.749
Brief.

622
00:34:26.056 --> 00:34:27.797
You have an update?

623
00:34:28.015 --> 00:34:30.104
As more systems come on line.
the introduction of variables

624
00:34:30.278 --> 00:34:32.367
still generates
a consistent outcome.

625
00:34:32.628 --> 00:34:34.369
Quantum entanglement
has <i>Enterprise</i> firmly anchored

626
00:34:34.543 --> 00:34:36.110
65 million years in the past.

627
00:34:36.284 --> 00:34:37.241
You're saying we're stuck here?

628
00:34:37.416 --> 00:34:39.983
Yes. And also no.

629
00:34:40.157 --> 00:34:41.071
The nature
of quantum entanglement

630
00:34:41.245 --> 00:34:42.421
could theoretically snap us

631
00:34:42.682 --> 00:34:43.552
right back
to the moment we left.

632
00:34:43.726 --> 00:34:44.727
Well. that seems good.

633
00:34:44.988 --> 00:34:46.729
However. to do so would require

634
00:34:46.903 --> 00:34:48.470
the power equivalent
of a supernova.

635
00:34:48.644 --> 00:34:50.646
the very same amount
that sent us here.

636
00:34:50.820 --> 00:34:52.953
Without it.
we are trapped in the past.

637
00:34:53.127 --> 00:34:54.520
- Less good.
- Indeed.

638
00:34:56.217 --> 00:34:57.218
<i>Captain. Commander Cassell</i>

639
00:34:57.392 --> 00:34:58.698
<i>and her guard have left the lab.</i>

640
00:34:58.872 --> 00:35:00.308
- Where did they go?
<i>- I don't know.</i>

641
00:35:00.613 --> 00:35:01.744
<i>They just phased
through the floor and were gone.</i>

642
00:35:01.918 --> 00:35:03.746
- Engineering.
- Pike to Engineering.

643
00:35:03.920 --> 00:35:05.269
What's happening down there?

644
00:35:05.574 --> 00:35:07.184
<i>That tall. scary Martian lady</i>

645
00:35:07.446 --> 00:35:08.925
<i>just came right through
the bulkhead and took it.</i>

646
00:35:09.099 --> 00:35:10.884
<i>- We couldn't stop her.</i>
- Took what?

647
00:35:11.101 --> 00:35:15.454
<i>The ship's primary
antimatter fuel cell.</i>

648
00:35:15.628 --> 00:35:17.368
Cassell's location keeps moving.

649
00:35:17.543 --> 00:35:19.632
Deck Ten.

650
00:35:19.806 --> 00:35:21.764
Deck Nine.

651
00:35:22.025 --> 00:35:24.680
Deck Eight. She's headed
for her egress point.

652
00:35:29.685 --> 00:35:30.599
I'm not armed.

653
00:35:30.773 --> 00:35:33.123
I just want to talk.

654
00:35:34.908 --> 00:35:36.126
We were helping you.

655
00:35:36.387 --> 00:35:38.651
and now you're taking
our fuel cell? Why?

656
00:35:42.263 --> 00:35:45.440
Captain...

657
00:35:45.614 --> 00:35:48.225
...I have been nothing
but honest with you.

658
00:35:48.487 --> 00:35:50.140
And consistent.

659
00:35:50.401 --> 00:35:52.969
You. however.
have not been equally truthful.

660
00:35:53.143 --> 00:35:54.144
What are you talking about?

661
00:35:54.318 --> 00:35:55.929
You spoke to me of Starfleet.

662
00:35:56.103 --> 00:35:57.844
of all that you've achieved.

663
00:35:58.018 --> 00:36:01.891
It was easy to get a sense
of your respect for your values.

664
00:36:02.065 --> 00:36:05.982
your deep feeling for those
you have fought for and loved.

665
00:36:06.156 --> 00:36:08.071
With these things
you were frank.

666
00:36:08.245 --> 00:36:11.335
You also spoke to me
of where you are from.

667
00:36:12.162 --> 00:36:14.730
But you failed to explain when.

668
00:36:15.514 --> 00:36:16.732
Your Federation doesn't exist.

669
00:36:16.906 --> 00:36:18.517
- That's not entirely true.
- Yet.

670
00:36:18.691 --> 00:36:20.823
It doesn't exist yet.

671
00:36:22.738 --> 00:36:23.826
You showed me your computer

672
00:36:24.131 --> 00:36:25.741
so I could speak
with the Dol'drm.

673
00:36:25.915 --> 00:36:28.439
It was simple
to understand from there

674
00:36:28.614 --> 00:36:30.920
how you determine time with it.

675
00:36:31.094 --> 00:36:35.098
Your Federation won't exist
for millions of years.

676
00:36:35.272 --> 00:36:38.449
And by then
my civilization will be gone.

677
00:36:38.624 --> 00:36:40.060
I'm sorry.

678
00:36:40.234 --> 00:36:41.452
Our regulations...

679
00:36:41.670 --> 00:36:43.367
they forbid me
from telling you that.

680
00:36:43.542 --> 00:36:45.718
But that doesn't mean
that we can't find a way

681
00:36:45.979 --> 00:36:48.068
- out of this for both of us.
- Captain.

682
00:36:48.895 --> 00:36:51.724
I understand you are trying
to save your people.

683
00:36:51.898 --> 00:36:54.204
As I am doing for mine.

684
00:36:54.378 --> 00:36:57.730
But we live now.
not in the future.

685
00:36:58.948 --> 00:37:00.907
Your ship's given us
exactly what we need

686
00:37:01.081 --> 00:37:03.039
to win our war.

687
00:37:04.693 --> 00:37:06.477
I'm sorry.

688
00:37:06.652 --> 00:37:08.218
Commander...

689
00:37:44.864 --> 00:37:47.910
This wreckage is apparently
the source of the iridium.

690
00:37:49.259 --> 00:37:52.045
And that's. like. an alien spaceship.

691
00:37:52.219 --> 00:37:54.134
On Earth.

692
00:37:54.308 --> 00:37:59.313
65 million years before us.

693
00:37:59.487 --> 00:38:02.272
I have to say this
out loud to believe it.

694
00:38:02.446 --> 00:38:05.885
Those burns... a weapon did that.

695
00:38:06.059 --> 00:38:07.626
It was shot down.

696
00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:10.237
- Our Martian friends?
- Mm-hmm.

697
00:38:11.934 --> 00:38:13.457
The iridium's inside.

698
00:38:13.806 --> 00:38:16.025
No life signs. but there
might be an engine compartment.

699
00:38:16.199 --> 00:38:17.592
Wait here.

700
00:38:43.444 --> 00:38:44.967
All these cryobeds?

701
00:38:45.141 --> 00:38:47.404
I think this was a colony ship.

702
00:38:55.108 --> 00:38:58.111
Must have all died on impact.

703
00:39:05.945 --> 00:39:07.163
Reflexes.

704
00:39:07.337 --> 00:39:09.470
They must all be dead.

705
00:39:10.514 --> 00:39:11.733
If they were settlers.

706
00:39:11.994 --> 00:39:14.518
I'm not sure
if I should feel sad or...

707
00:39:15.955 --> 00:39:17.304
...relieved.

708
00:39:18.784 --> 00:39:21.395
Whatever the reason
they were in cryosleep.

709
00:39:21.569 --> 00:39:24.790
they were shot down and died
on a planet far from home.

710
00:39:25.051 --> 00:39:26.617
headed who knows where.

711
00:39:26.792 --> 00:39:28.968
They may be
different from us. but...

712
00:39:30.186 --> 00:39:32.449
...they wanted to survive. too.

713
00:39:34.669 --> 00:39:36.236
Iridium fuel pod.

714
00:39:36.410 --> 00:39:37.846
The only one
that wasn't damaged.

715
00:39:38.020 --> 00:39:39.282
Let's hope Scotty and Pelia

716
00:39:39.543 --> 00:39:40.370
can jury-rig it
to the <i>Enterprise.</i>

717
00:39:40.544 --> 00:39:41.763
Can we go now. please?

718
00:39:41.937 --> 00:39:43.460
This place
is giving me the creeps.

719
00:39:43.634 --> 00:39:45.114
Yeah.

720
00:40:12.185 --> 00:40:14.317
You just punched it.

721
00:40:14.491 --> 00:40:18.321
Yeah. well. I didn't have time
to shoot it in the mouth. did I?

722
00:40:20.323 --> 00:40:22.978
Well. if you two are finished
just standing here...

723
00:40:25.372 --> 00:40:28.114
<i>Hey. I've managed to hook up
the backup antimatter pod.</i>

724
00:40:28.288 --> 00:40:29.898
<i>You gotta hurry up
with that iridium.</i>

725
00:40:30.072 --> 00:40:32.553
Yeah. yeah. we're coming. Geez.

726
00:40:51.702 --> 00:40:54.053
You punched a dinosaur?

727
00:40:55.619 --> 00:40:57.012
Well.

728
00:40:57.273 --> 00:40:58.579
I'm sure it had it coming.

729
00:41:02.148 --> 00:41:03.584
What is it?

730
00:41:03.932 --> 00:41:07.196
It's just. I broke my hand
and I don't feel any pain.

731
00:41:07.370 --> 00:41:09.459
Well. how is that possible?

732
00:41:09.633 --> 00:41:10.896
It isn't.

733
00:41:11.157 --> 00:41:13.072
The truth is.

734
00:41:13.246 --> 00:41:15.465
I've felt different
for a while now.

735
00:41:15.639 --> 00:41:17.598
I-I've always had
elevated strength and reflexes.

736
00:41:17.859 --> 00:41:19.600
but now it's-it's almost like

737
00:41:19.774 --> 00:41:22.037
my whole body
feels more attuned.

738
00:41:22.951 --> 00:41:24.257
And your mind?

739
00:41:24.431 --> 00:41:25.824
Confused.

740
00:41:25.998 --> 00:41:29.915
Look. I carry
recessive augmented DNA. right?

741
00:41:30.089 --> 00:41:31.786
Now. is it possible that somehow

742
00:41:31.960 --> 00:41:36.704
all I've been through has
activated those recessive genes?

743
00:41:36.878 --> 00:41:39.968
Are you going to try
and take over the galaxy now?

744
00:41:40.882 --> 00:41:42.231
I don't know.

745
00:41:42.579 --> 00:41:45.800
Hey. You may be carrying
enhanced warrior genes.

746
00:41:45.974 --> 00:41:48.803
but it's not who you are.

747
00:41:51.501 --> 00:41:53.286
I've got to go.

748
00:41:57.812 --> 00:42:00.510
Iridium is installed and ready to function.

749
00:42:00.684 --> 00:42:02.861
as long as we don't want
to double-check it.

750
00:42:03.035 --> 00:42:04.253
Do we need to double-check it?

751
00:42:04.514 --> 00:42:05.951
We need to get a fix
on that Martian ship.

752
00:42:06.125 --> 00:42:08.431
Are you concerned
or are you worried. Mr. Scott?

753
00:42:08.605 --> 00:42:09.606
Just worried. sir.

754
00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:11.130
Good man.

755
00:42:11.304 --> 00:42:12.914
Bridge is coming back on line.

756
00:42:13.088 --> 00:42:15.264
- Long-range sensors?
- Reinitializing.

757
00:42:15.525 --> 00:42:17.092
- Time?
- 15 seconds.

758
00:42:17.266 --> 00:42:18.398
Every second could be
getting Commander Cassell

759
00:42:18.572 --> 00:42:20.313
closer to detonating
that antimatter.

760
00:42:20.487 --> 00:42:21.923
Well. I can't get power
to the ship's systems

761
00:42:22.097 --> 00:42:23.577
any faster. Captain.

762
00:42:25.405 --> 00:42:27.102
- Screens are working. Chris.
- Great. How about

763
00:42:27.363 --> 00:42:30.192
- long-range comms?
- On and functioning. sir. Orders?

764
00:42:30.366 --> 00:42:32.325
Connect the Martian ship.

765
00:42:32.586 --> 00:42:33.717
Hailing them.

766
00:42:33.892 --> 00:42:35.894
And initializing
ship-to-ship visuals.

767
00:42:36.068 --> 00:42:37.547
Commander Cassell.
this is Captain Pike

768
00:42:37.721 --> 00:42:39.332
of the USS <i>Enterprise.</i>

769
00:42:40.681 --> 00:42:42.857
I should have told you where...

770
00:42:43.031 --> 00:42:44.990
when we're from.

771
00:42:45.251 --> 00:42:46.992
I should have been honest.
because then you might have

772
00:42:47.166 --> 00:42:48.384
believed me
about everything else.

773
00:42:48.558 --> 00:42:50.386
There are other ways
of solving conflict.

774
00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:52.084
I understand how you...

775
00:42:52.562 --> 00:42:54.303
<i>Captain. you have lost crewmates?</i>

776
00:42:54.477 --> 00:42:56.566
<i>- Friends?</i>
- Yes. Many.

777
00:42:56.740 --> 00:42:59.047
<i>Imagine those losses
a thousandfold.</i>

778
00:42:59.221 --> 00:43:02.964
<i>Imagine a wound on your planet
that will never heal.</i>

779
00:43:03.138 --> 00:43:06.794
<i>A memorial to millions of dead
etched in rock and blood.</i>

780
00:43:06.968 --> 00:43:11.190
I know you believe
that what you're doing is right.

781
00:43:11.364 --> 00:43:13.888
But I have seen a future
where species can coexist.

782
00:43:14.062 --> 00:43:15.629
<i>And I have seen one
on your computers</i>

783
00:43:15.803 --> 00:43:18.806
<i>where my homeworld
is a barren red wasteland.</i>

784
00:43:20.286 --> 00:43:22.375
<i>Can you tell me the Dol'drm
are not responsible for that?</i>

785
00:43:22.549 --> 00:43:24.116
No. I can't.

786
00:43:24.290 --> 00:43:26.466
But I can tell you
that if you use our technology

787
00:43:26.640 --> 00:43:29.686
to change the future.
millions of lives may be lost.

788
00:43:29.948 --> 00:43:32.428
<i>And millions of lives
may be saved.</i>

789
00:43:32.602 --> 00:43:35.040
<i>The lives of my people.</i>

790
00:43:35.214 --> 00:43:37.607
<i>Isn't that what a captain does?</i>

791
00:43:37.781 --> 00:43:39.783
<i>Save her people?</i>

792
00:43:40.654 --> 00:43:43.700
<i>Wouldn't you?</i>

793
00:43:43.874 --> 00:43:46.094
Uh. she shut off her comms.

794
00:43:46.355 --> 00:43:47.791
And they're not
responding to hails.

795
00:43:47.966 --> 00:43:49.054
- Engines?
- Half-impulse.

796
00:43:49.228 --> 00:43:50.577
Erica. plot an intercept course.

797
00:43:50.751 --> 00:43:52.144
We're gonna try
to stop them from using

798
00:43:52.361 --> 00:43:53.536
- our antimatter.
- The only question is.

799
00:43:53.710 --> 00:43:55.190
where are they planning
to use it?

800
00:43:55.364 --> 00:43:56.975
They don't have warp.
Where is this enemy planet?

801
00:43:57.149 --> 00:43:58.237
Long-range sensors
are fully operational.

802
00:43:58.411 --> 00:44:00.456
Extrapolating their course.

803
00:44:01.414 --> 00:44:03.155
They are headed for
the fifth planet in the system.

804
00:44:03.329 --> 00:44:05.548
- Jupiter?
- No. this planet is much smaller.

805
00:44:05.809 --> 00:44:07.072
Similar to Mars.

806
00:44:07.420 --> 00:44:09.030
At a distance of
480 million kilometers from Sol

807
00:44:09.204 --> 00:44:10.901
and 120 million kilometers
from the Martian solar rotation.

808
00:44:11.076 --> 00:44:13.339
But there's no fifth planet
like that in our solar system.

809
00:44:13.513 --> 00:44:17.256
The planet is populated
by billions of life-forms.

810
00:44:17.430 --> 00:44:19.388
An arachnid species.

811
00:44:20.128 --> 00:44:24.132
That's what we found crashed
on Earth. with the iridium.

812
00:44:25.438 --> 00:44:26.830
The fifth planet
of our solar system

813
00:44:27.005 --> 00:44:28.267
is the Dol'drm homeworld.

814
00:44:28.441 --> 00:44:30.138
Captain. the Martian warship
is approaching

815
00:44:30.312 --> 00:44:32.619
the fifth planet
at high impulse.

816
00:44:32.793 --> 00:44:34.577
On screen.

817
00:44:36.666 --> 00:44:38.016
We will be in firing range

818
00:44:38.277 --> 00:44:39.495
of the Martian ship
in less than one minute.

819
00:44:39.669 --> 00:44:40.714
Phasers aren't working yet.

820
00:44:40.888 --> 00:44:42.281
We just need to disable

821
00:44:42.498 --> 00:44:44.239
the Martian ship.
Can we try a tractor beam?

822
00:44:44.500 --> 00:44:45.458
- There's not enough power at this range.
- Photon torpedoes?

823
00:44:45.632 --> 00:44:46.676
We need something.

824
00:44:46.850 --> 00:44:48.113
- Checking.
- Captain.

825
00:44:48.374 --> 00:44:50.028
my calculations indicate
that if the Martians

826
00:44:50.202 --> 00:44:51.594
detonate our antimatter pod
at their current proximity.

827
00:44:51.768 --> 00:44:53.901
they will be unable
to escape the explosion.

828
00:44:54.902 --> 00:44:57.296
It's her only way
to guarantee a kill shot.

829
00:44:57.470 --> 00:44:59.080
She's gonna sacrifice
her ship and her crew

830
00:44:59.254 --> 00:45:00.603
to destroy the planet.

831
00:45:00.908 --> 00:45:02.518
Captain. I think
we have enough power

832
00:45:02.692 --> 00:45:03.824
- to fire one photon torpedo.
- As soon as we're in range.

833
00:45:03.998 --> 00:45:05.521
The Martian ship just activated

834
00:45:05.695 --> 00:45:07.349
a missile launcher.

835
00:45:10.483 --> 00:45:12.354
They have deployed
the antimatter.

836
00:45:22.886 --> 00:45:24.149
Can we shoot it down
without detonating it?

837
00:45:24.410 --> 00:45:25.454
Yes. but we're still
not in range.

838
00:45:25.628 --> 00:45:26.760
Spock. how long to impact?

839
00:45:26.934 --> 00:45:28.501
- 30 seconds.
- Erica.

840
00:45:28.805 --> 00:45:30.024
give it everything you've got.
Push it right to the edge.

841
00:45:30.198 --> 00:45:31.591
- We have to get in range.
- Aye. sir.

842
00:45:31.765 --> 00:45:33.375
Come on. baby. You've got this.

843
00:45:33.549 --> 00:45:35.116
- 20 seconds to impact.
- Erica?

844
00:45:35.290 --> 00:45:36.509
Pegging the redline. sir.

845
00:45:36.683 --> 00:45:38.641
There's a reason
for those lights.

846
00:45:38.815 --> 00:45:40.774
- Shut them off. Scotty.
- Sir. we're in range.

847
00:45:40.948 --> 00:45:42.558
Locking photon torpedo
on target.

848
00:45:42.819 --> 00:45:43.951
- 12 seconds to impact.
- Target locked.

849
00:45:44.125 --> 00:45:45.518
We've got it. sir.

850
00:45:49.043 --> 00:45:50.653
Captain.

851
00:45:50.827 --> 00:45:53.178
Fire. sir?

852
00:45:57.834 --> 00:45:59.619
Do not fire.
Repeat. do not fire.

853
00:45:59.793 --> 00:46:02.404
- But. sir... - Captain. that planet's
about to be destroyed

854
00:46:02.578 --> 00:46:03.753
by our technology.

855
00:46:04.014 --> 00:46:05.755
Our future's at stake.
We must fire.

856
00:46:05.929 --> 00:46:08.193
You heard my order. Hold fire.
stand down photon torpedo.

857
00:46:08.367 --> 00:46:09.977
Chris. our future
notwithstanding.

858
00:46:10.238 --> 00:46:12.849
we can't just sit here and let
that entire planet be destroyed.

859
00:46:13.023 --> 00:46:14.938
In our future...

860
00:46:15.809 --> 00:46:18.116
...there is no fifth planet.

861
00:46:18.290 --> 00:46:19.769
Three seconds.

862
00:46:20.901 --> 00:46:23.251
Two. One.

863
00:46:57.590 --> 00:46:59.157
I'm sorry.

864
00:47:05.989 --> 00:47:07.600
That blast wave's gonna hit us.

865
00:47:07.861 --> 00:47:10.168
But I think I can outrun it.

866
00:47:10.342 --> 00:47:11.995
No. We should not run.

867
00:47:12.170 --> 00:47:13.910
We need to head
into the blast wave.

868
00:47:14.084 --> 00:47:15.477
Head into that?

869
00:47:15.651 --> 00:47:17.392
You saw what just happened
to the Martian ship.

870
00:47:17.566 --> 00:47:20.178
We may be able to use it
to send us back to our time.

871
00:47:20.352 --> 00:47:22.223
The antimatter explosion.
combined with the explosion

872
00:47:22.397 --> 00:47:24.269
of the planet's core.
has created the necessary energy

873
00:47:24.443 --> 00:47:26.358
to free <i>Enterprise</i>
from this temporal anchor point.

874
00:47:26.532 --> 00:47:28.229
snapping
the quantum entanglement

875
00:47:28.403 --> 00:47:29.970
back to the exact point
we came from.

876
00:47:30.144 --> 00:47:32.320
Before the blast wave
tears our ship apart?

877
00:47:32.494 --> 00:47:33.887
Unknown.

878
00:47:34.235 --> 00:47:37.630
But it is our only option
if we intend to go home.

879
00:47:39.284 --> 00:47:41.111
Erica. come about.

880
00:47:41.286 --> 00:47:43.288
Take us straight
into the blast wave.

881
00:47:43.462 --> 00:47:46.073
Spock. if you have any
calculations. now's the time.

882
00:47:46.856 --> 00:47:49.337
Helm. come to course 1-4-7.
mark 2.

883
00:47:51.339 --> 00:47:52.688
Roger that.

884
00:47:52.862 --> 00:47:55.996
Everybody. hang on to something.

885
00:47:56.170 --> 00:47:57.476
Anything.

886
00:47:59.086 --> 00:48:00.696
Everything.

887
00:48:54.794 --> 00:48:56.361
After running multiple simulations.

888
00:48:56.535 --> 00:48:58.754
I determined that a fragment
from the Dol'drm planet

889
00:48:58.928 --> 00:49:00.495
is the Chicxulub asteroid.

890
00:49:00.669 --> 00:49:02.628
<i>The</i> one that hit Earth

891
00:49:02.802 --> 00:49:04.238
65 million years ago?

892
00:49:04.586 --> 00:49:07.937
And led to the extinction
of the dinosaurs.

893
00:49:08.111 --> 00:49:09.417
Does that mean...

894
00:49:09.678 --> 00:49:10.810
Yes.

895
00:49:11.114 --> 00:49:13.116
The remaining debris.
less than four percent

896
00:49:13.291 --> 00:49:14.553
of the planet's original mass.

897
00:49:14.727 --> 00:49:16.337
eventually became part
of the asteroid belt

898
00:49:16.511 --> 00:49:17.947
as we have come to know it.

899
00:49:18.121 --> 00:49:19.514
Furthermore.
the absence of the planet

900
00:49:19.688 --> 00:49:21.255
caused a gravimetric shift
in the system.

901
00:49:21.429 --> 00:49:23.083
moving Mars
further from the sun.

902
00:49:23.257 --> 00:49:26.173
Its atmosphere cooled to become
the Mars we know today.

903
00:49:26.347 --> 00:49:30.090
Earth also cooled.
ushering in the Cenozoic Era.

904
00:49:30.264 --> 00:49:31.961
and eventually...

905
00:49:32.135 --> 00:49:34.312
The evolution of humanity.

906
00:49:36.444 --> 00:49:39.752
Even I remember a part of that.

907
00:49:40.013 --> 00:49:42.320
So. we only exist

908
00:49:42.494 --> 00:49:45.671
because of what we did?

909
00:49:45.845 --> 00:49:49.239
I think we might exist
because of what we didn't do.

910
00:49:49.414 --> 00:49:52.721
The Martians
had to take our weapons.

911
00:49:52.895 --> 00:49:56.986
And we had to let them destroy
the Dol'drm planet.

912
00:49:58.336 --> 00:50:00.468
Because they always have.

913
00:50:01.904 --> 00:50:03.515
We were always there.

914
00:50:04.690 --> 00:50:06.822
So we were never in danger
of changing anything?

915
00:50:06.996 --> 00:50:08.694
O-Or were we?

916
00:50:08.868 --> 00:50:10.391
What about Commander Cassell?

917
00:50:10.565 --> 00:50:13.525
Did she destroy her own planet?

918
00:50:19.792 --> 00:50:21.359
I think...

919
00:50:22.142 --> 00:50:24.144
...we could all use a night off.

920
00:50:26.276 --> 00:50:28.496
Yeah. I heard it.

921
00:50:28.670 --> 00:50:30.411
Let's go before
he changes his mind.

922
00:50:30.585 --> 00:50:32.500
Mm-hmm.

923
00:50:32.674 --> 00:50:34.546
You're all dismissed.

924
00:50:38.114 --> 00:50:39.507
Thank you.

925
00:50:48.516 --> 00:50:51.171
Commander Cassell.

926
00:50:53.782 --> 00:50:55.262
She just wanted
to save her own people.

927
00:50:55.436 --> 00:50:58.134
I would have done
exactly the same thing.

928
00:50:58.308 --> 00:50:59.875
And now they're all gone.

929
00:51:00.136 --> 00:51:02.835
without a trace
of their ever having existed.

930
00:51:03.096 --> 00:51:05.533
Not entirely.

931
00:51:07.143 --> 00:51:10.712
I ran Cassell's DNA
through our database.

932
00:51:11.452 --> 00:51:13.411
It appears that Martian DNA
is present

933
00:51:13.585 --> 00:51:16.414
in innumerable species
throughout the galaxy.

934
00:51:16.588 --> 00:51:18.111
They escaped?

935
00:51:18.285 --> 00:51:19.721
Some. at least.

936
00:51:19.982 --> 00:51:22.550
The commander
may not have survived.

937
00:51:22.724 --> 00:51:24.247
but her people did.

938
00:51:24.422 --> 00:51:26.685
And the Dol'drm?

939
00:51:28.164 --> 00:51:32.342
If their planet
had remained in the system.

940
00:51:32.517 --> 00:51:36.303
entire histories
would be erased.

941
00:51:36.477 --> 00:51:39.262
Trillions of lives.

942
00:51:40.481 --> 00:51:42.788
Evolutions undone.

943
00:51:42.962 --> 00:51:44.746
Yeah. but...

944
00:51:46.356 --> 00:51:49.447
I didn't know that in the moment
that I made that call.

945
00:51:51.971 --> 00:51:54.582
It was a hunch...
it was a good one. but...

946
00:51:54.756 --> 00:51:56.192
but I had no data.

947
00:51:56.366 --> 00:51:59.631
You. more than anyone
that I know.

948
00:51:59.805 --> 00:52:03.635
have thought about the past
and the future a great deal.

949
00:52:05.637 --> 00:52:08.335
But most of us live in the now.

950
00:52:10.424 --> 00:52:11.947
I guess...

951
00:52:12.948 --> 00:52:15.995
...never slowing down.
never stopping...

952
00:52:17.736 --> 00:52:20.434
...it's been quieter
than being in my head.

953
00:52:21.304 --> 00:52:24.307
A bit of unsolicited advice.

954
00:52:26.875 --> 00:52:29.530
Find a way to make peace
with both.

955
00:52:46.373 --> 00:52:49.202
<i>A Princess of Mars.</i>

956
00:52:50.029 --> 00:52:52.031
Who knew that book
would be so prophetic?

957
00:52:54.381 --> 00:52:56.688
"I have ever been prone
to seek adventure

958
00:52:56.949 --> 00:52:59.386
"and to investigate
and experiment.

959
00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:03.521
where wiser men would have
left well enough alone."

960
00:53:05.914 --> 00:53:07.699
Love this book.

961
00:53:08.743 --> 00:53:10.484
My father... he-he always
laughed at the idea

962
00:53:10.745 --> 00:53:13.792
of Martians existing
before Federation terraforming.

963
00:53:14.967 --> 00:53:18.057
Ugh. if I could just go back
and tell him now.

964
00:53:18.231 --> 00:53:21.539
I think one time-travel
adventure a day is enough.

965
00:53:21.713 --> 00:53:24.759
And this one needs
to stay a secret.

966
00:53:24.933 --> 00:53:26.282
Thought you'd say that.

967
00:53:26.587 --> 00:53:27.849
Well. if it were up to me.
everyone would know

968
00:53:28.023 --> 00:53:29.198
that the <i>Enterprise</i>
was responsible

969
00:53:29.372 --> 00:53:30.765
for humanity's origin.

970
00:53:31.070 --> 00:53:33.463
But the Federation Council
might want us to pause

971
00:53:33.638 --> 00:53:36.597
before we rush in
to amend history books.

972
00:53:36.771 --> 00:53:38.556
So. what do we say?

973
00:53:39.382 --> 00:53:40.819
The truth.

974
00:53:41.602 --> 00:53:44.344
We lost contact with your ship
for a few moments.

975
00:53:44.605 --> 00:53:47.913
Then the solar storm collapsed.
exploded and vanished.

976
00:53:48.087 --> 00:53:51.569
By the time the ensuing
gamma-ray burst had dissipated.

977
00:53:51.743 --> 00:53:54.659
communication with the
<i>Enterprise</i> was reestablished.

978
00:53:54.920 --> 00:53:57.009
And what about...

979
00:53:57.836 --> 00:54:01.579
...us answering our own Mayday

980
00:54:01.753 --> 00:54:07.280
from a subspace buoy we deployed
65 million years ago?

981
00:54:07.454 --> 00:54:10.239
One sent here
by a storm that we created

982
00:54:10.413 --> 00:54:13.895
after it sent us back in time.

983
00:54:16.158 --> 00:54:17.638
Chris.

984
00:54:17.812 --> 00:54:19.858
everything happened
as it was meant to.

985
00:54:20.032 --> 00:54:22.425
That much is clear.

986
00:54:22.600 --> 00:54:24.123
So don't overthink it.

987
00:54:26.734 --> 00:54:28.562
What about the promotion?

988
00:54:28.736 --> 00:54:31.478
Hmm? Had any time to consider?

989
00:54:32.914 --> 00:54:35.743
Yeah.

990
00:54:35.917 --> 00:54:37.789
I saw the past.
present and future

991
00:54:38.050 --> 00:54:42.010
in a way that I never
thought possible.

992
00:54:43.664 --> 00:54:45.710
I want to focus on my now.

993
00:54:45.884 --> 00:54:49.452
and that's here with <i>Enterprise.</i>

994
00:54:49.627 --> 00:54:51.933
I'm not ready for the promotion.

995
00:54:53.456 --> 00:54:55.197
But...

996
00:54:56.111 --> 00:54:58.331
...I know someone else who is.

997
00:54:59.158 --> 00:55:01.464
I... That's...

998
00:55:02.248 --> 00:55:03.510
Chris.

999
00:55:03.771 --> 00:55:06.687
Eh. you don't have
to say anything.

1000
00:55:06.861 --> 00:55:08.863
So I'll say it.

1001
00:55:09.037 --> 00:55:12.911
To Commander Una Chin-Riley.

1002
00:55:13.085 --> 00:55:14.390
Congratulations
on your promotion.

1003
00:55:14.564 --> 00:55:16.392
You more than deserve it.

1004
00:55:16.566 --> 00:55:18.525
One step closer to captain

1005
00:55:18.699 --> 00:55:21.789
and your own starship.

1006
00:55:26.141 --> 00:55:27.490
Cadet.

1007
00:55:27.665 --> 00:55:29.275
I wanted to see
how you're feeling

1008
00:55:29.449 --> 00:55:32.452
after your first real adventure
on the <i>Enterprise.</i>

1009
00:55:32.626 --> 00:55:35.498
I have learned that Starfleet
is not what I expected.

1010
00:55:35.673 --> 00:55:37.892
Oh. it can surprise you.

1011
00:55:38.066 --> 00:55:40.634
My family was disappointed
that I was not placed

1012
00:55:40.895 --> 00:55:42.288
at the Vulcan Science Academy.

1013
00:55:42.549 --> 00:55:45.160
I thought this would be
a good alternative.

1014
00:55:45.334 --> 00:55:47.249
Well. it very well could be.

1015
00:55:47.423 --> 00:55:48.860
It is not.

1016
00:55:49.121 --> 00:55:51.601
I now understand why
my parents were disappointed.

1017
00:55:51.776 --> 00:55:52.994
This is a chaotic place.

1018
00:55:53.299 --> 00:55:55.344
It likely helps that Spock
is part human.

1019
00:55:55.518 --> 00:55:56.955
I. however. am not.

1020
00:55:57.129 --> 00:55:58.826
Thank you
for your questions. Ensign.

1021
00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:01.655
but any further
are not necessary.

1022
00:56:05.441 --> 00:56:06.399
Honestly?

1023
00:56:06.573 --> 00:56:08.836
She might just be very Vulcan.

1024
00:56:09.010 --> 00:56:10.533
That's all.

1025
00:56:10.708 --> 00:56:12.971
It's gonna be a long year.

1026
00:56:13.145 --> 00:56:16.061
Come on. La'An and Una and I
are gonna talk about dinosaurs.

1027
00:56:16.235 --> 00:56:18.411
Way more worth your time.

1028
00:56:21.675 --> 00:56:22.763
Scotty.

1029
00:56:22.937 --> 00:56:25.157
Are you gonna...

1030
00:56:26.027 --> 00:56:27.594
Say sorry?

1031
00:56:27.812 --> 00:56:29.727
You wrench jockeys are kind of
sensitive. aren't you?

1032
00:56:29.901 --> 00:56:31.641
Frickin' engineers.

1033
00:56:31.903 --> 00:56:33.818
Bloody pilots.

1034
00:56:45.655 --> 00:56:47.570
So...

1035
00:56:47.745 --> 00:56:50.878
are you guys gonna tell us
about the dinosaurs?

1036
00:56:51.052 --> 00:56:51.966
Oh. yeah.

1037
00:56:54.099 --> 00:56:55.927
Come on.

1038
00:56:59.191 --> 00:57:04.196
It was... something.

1039
00:57:06.328 --> 00:57:09.462
<i>We've seen a lot
of strange new worlds.</i>

1040
00:57:09.636 --> 00:57:13.901
<i>but we'll never see something
like this again.</i>

